{
  "doc_id": "45015",
  "text": "HUCB has established itself as a legitimate source for hematopoietic stem cell transplantations in the treatment of hematological disorders. [CITATION_1] Besides this clinical use, neurological disorders such as trauma, stroke and neurodegenerative diseases, may represent another challenge for cell-based regenerative medicine using HUCB and derived progenitors. Studies by a number of groups support the idea that infusion of HUCB in animal models ameliorate central nervous system damage induced by hemorrhagic brain injury, [CITATION_2] heatstroke, [CITATION_3] middle cerebral artery occlusion, 51 traumatic brain injury [CITATION_4] and laminectomy spinal cord injury. [CITATION_5] In the injured brain a variety of cytokines including IFN-g 54 as well as neurotrophins such as NGF, [CITATION_6] were found to be released by glial cells and infiltrating hematopoietic inflammatory cells. In this inflammatory environment, HUCB and derived neuronal progenitors may encounter a gradient of IFN-g and NGF on transplantation, and may respond by commitment to differentiation as presently found in vitro, providing a regenerative and/or neuroprotective effect. The present HUCBNP cells, both undifferentiated and differentiated, were recently found by our group to confer neuroprotection to neurons found under ischemic insults. [CITATION_7] It is interesting to note that the mechanism of neuroprotectin was related to production of anti-oxidants and release of NGF, bFGF and VEGF. [CITATION_8] Neurochemical and electrophysiological properties of HUCBNP are presently under investigation in our laboratory. Future experiments of HUCBNP implantation in damaged brain areas in animal models will uncover their neuroprotective mechanism, either by a bystander effect as found in vitro [CITATION_9] or by reconstitution of neuronal pathways.",
